        "title": "Too many — the LORD reduces His own army",
        "range": "7:1-8",
        "excerpt": "The Lord said to Gideon, 'The people who are with you are too many for Me to give Midian into their hands, for Israel would become boastful, saying, My own power has delivered me.'",
        "body": "Chapter 7 opens with Gideon — now called by his theophoric alternate name Jerubbaal ('let Baal contend') as a quiet reminder that the man leading this army has already proven willing to act against false gods (6:25-32) — rising early and camping at the spring of Harod. The Midianite host is arrayed across the Jezreel Valley by the hill of Moreh. The Hebrew narrator paints the picture spatially: Israel high on the slope of Gilboa, Midian spread below like a sea of tents. By any conventional reckoning Israel is hopelessly outnumbered; 32,000 against a force later described as *like locusts* (v.12).\n\nThen the LORD speaks, and the speech reverses every military calculation. *The people who are with you are too many.* Not too few — too *many*. The reason given is doxological, not strategic: *lest Israel become boastful, saying, My own hand has delivered me* (v.2). This single sentence is the chapter's thesis and arguably the theological center of the Gideon narrative. God is not indifferent to *who* gets the credit for His deliverances. The whole point of raising up a judge after seven years of Midianite oppression (6:1) was Israel's recognition that the LORD alone saves; a victory that produced national boasting would defeat that purpose at the moment of its apparent fulfillment.\n\nThe first reduction (v.3) follows Deuteronomy 20:8 — the fearful are sent home. Twenty-two thousand leave; ten thousand remain. The narrator's restraint here is telling: he gives no commentary on those who left, no rebuke, no moral evaluation. They are simply removed. They are not the chapter's problem. The remaining ten thousand are. The LORD's second declaration — *the people are still too many* (v.4) — exposes that the issue was never cowardice but quantity. Any army large enough to credit itself is too large.\n\nThe second reduction (vv.5-7) is divine and unexplained. The water test produces a 300/9,700 split based on a criterion the text refuses to interpret. Did the lappers stay alert by drinking from the hand while watching the horizon, as some commentators suggest? Did they kneel less because they were too proud, or too eager, or simply too few to matter? The narrator does not say, and his silence is the point. If the criterion were stated, the 300 could claim merit. By leaving it opaque, the text protects the doctrine it has just articulated: God's selection is His own, by His own measure, for His own glory. The 300 are kept not because they earned it but because He chose them.\n\nVerse 8 closes the panel with a stark visual: the 300 take *the people's provisions and their trumpets* — they inherit the supplies and the worship-horns of the dismissed thousands — and the rest of Israel is sent away. Gideon stands on the slope above the valley with three hundred men, a heap of borrowed gear, and the LORD's promise: *'I will deliver you with the 300.'* The reduction is finished. The doctrine is enforced. The battle is yet to come.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rav* (too many, vv. 2, 4) is the same word used of Pharaoh's anxiety in Exodus 1:9 — *'the sons of Israel are too many'*; the irony is that what worries Pharaoh worries the LORD too, but for inverse reasons. *Paar* (boastful, glorify oneself) is the verb later used negatively of human pride in Isaiah 10:15. *Yasah* (save, v.2) is the root of *Yeshua*; the chapter's central question is whose hand will *save*."
