        "title": "The pursuit — rout, fords, and the heads of the princes",
        "range": "7:23-25",
        "excerpt": "They captured the two leaders of Midian, Oreb and Zeeb, and they killed Oreb at the rock of Oreb, and they killed Zeeb at the wine press of Zeeb.",
        "body": "The fourth movement transitions from supernatural rout to coordinated pursuit. The Midianites flee southeast across the Jezreel Valley — to Beth-shittah, Zererah, the edge of Abel-meholah, by Tabbath (v.22) — heading for the Jordan fords by which they had originally crossed into Israel. The tribes who were dismissed at the start of the chapter (Naphtali, Asher, all Manasseh) are now summoned for the chase (v.23). The original 32,000 — or whatever remains of them — are called back not for the battle but for the mop-up. The LORD's pattern holds: the salvation is His; the cleanup is the people's.\n\nGideon also sends messengers throughout the hill country of Ephraim (v.24), the tribe deliberately not invited to the initial muster (a slight Ephraim will hold against him in 8:1). Ephraim seizes the Jordan crossings at Beth-barah and traps the fleeing Midianites against the water. The two Midianite princes — Oreb (*Raven*) and Zeeb (*Wolf*), names of birds and beasts of prey, fittingly given to oppressors who have descended on Israel's harvests like scavengers — are captured and executed. The named landmarks remain: *the rock of Oreb* and *the winepress of Zeeb* become local memorials that will still be cited centuries later by Asaph (Psalm 83:11) and Isaiah (Isaiah 10:26).\n\nThe chapter closes with Ephraim bringing the severed heads of Oreb and Zeeb to Gideon *from across the Jordan* (v.25). This is the trophy moment — the visible token of victory. But notice what the narrator does *not* say. He does not say Gideon rejoiced. He does not say Gideon worshiped (as in v.15). He does not say Gideon attributed the victory to the LORD. The chapter ends in trophy-display, and the next chapter will open with Ephraim's complaint (8:1) and Gideon's increasingly fraught negotiations with the eastern towns (8:4-17), culminating in his refusal of kingship that is in fact a refusal *of the name* but not of the substance (8:22-27). The man who bowed in worship in 7:15 is about to make an ephod that becomes a snare to all Israel (8:27).\n\nJudges 7 is therefore Gideon's apex and Israel's archetype. As an apex, it shows what faith looks like when it acts on the LORD's reduction, hears the LORD's confirmation, and trusts the LORD's strange weapons. As an archetype, it provides the language by which later Scripture interprets every great deliverance — the breaking of the yoke of Midian (Isaiah 9:4) becomes the figure for Messianic salvation, accomplished not by armies but by the LORD Himself working through what looks contemptible to the world. Paul writes 1 Corinthians 1:26-31 with Judges 7 in his theological bloodstream. The cross is the ultimate barley loaf — the despised thing by which the camp of every enemy falls.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Radaph* (pursued, vv. 23, 25) is the standard verb for military pursuit, used here of the tribes chasing the routed enemy. *Lakhad* (captured, vv. 24, 25) is the verb for *seizing* a city, fortress, or person — the Ephraimite capture is decisive and forensic. The personal names *Orev* (Raven) and *Zeev* (Wolf) are typical of predatory naming patterns in the ancient Near East; the narrator uses them to score a quiet point — the carrion birds and wolves who have feasted on Israel are themselves now killed and named for the places of their slaughter."
